[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":498},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F12\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F12\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F12\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F12\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope\u002F":473,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F12\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope\u002F":482},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200412\u002F2694164006\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":456,"date":457,"description":458,"extension":459,"lang":460,"meta":461,"navigation":168,"path":462,"readingMinutes":463,"seo":464,"standalone":465,"stem":466,"tags":467,"tldr":470,"updated":457,"url":471,"__hash__":472},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-03-lexical-scope.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (3): Lexical Scope — Where You Declare It Is Where It Lives","1000578090",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":450},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,31,34,37,40,108,111,114,182,186,189,195,198,204,207,210,308,333,336,412,429,433,446],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"JavaScript uses lexical scope. In short, lexical scope means the scope of something is decided the moment you declare it.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"lexical-scope","Lexical Scope",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":29,"src":30},"Lexical scope","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-12%2015.50.21.png",[17,32,33],{},"Lexical scope is a really important concept in JavaScript. When you declare something, its scope is already decided right there. Before we go further, let me quickly cover what scope actually means.",[17,35,36],{},"Lexical scope is basically the place where something physically lives — think the global environment versus a local environment.",[17,38,39],{},"Here's a quick example of a local environment:",[41,42,47],"pre",{"className":43,"code":44,"language":45,"meta":46,"style":46},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function sayHi() {\n  var name = 'Ray';\n}\nconsole.log(name); \u002F\u002F name is not defined;\n","js","",[48,49,50,67,86,92],"code",{"__ignoreMap":46},[51,52,55,59,63],"span",{"class":53,"line":54},"line",1,[51,56,58],{"class":57},"sWyjQ","function",[51,60,62],{"class":61},"sj_SG"," sayHi",[51,64,66],{"class":65},"sMAXC","() {\n",[51,68,70,73,76,79,83],{"class":53,"line":69},2,[51,71,72],{"class":57},"  var",[51,74,75],{"class":65}," name ",[51,77,78],{"class":57},"=",[51,80,82],{"class":81},"sTRMh"," 'Ray'",[51,84,85],{"class":65},";\n",[51,87,89],{"class":53,"line":88},3,[51,90,91],{"class":65},"}\n",[51,93,95,98,101,104],{"class":53,"line":94},4,[51,96,97],{"class":65},"console.",[51,99,100],{"class":61},"log",[51,102,103],{"class":65},"(name); ",[51,105,107],{"class":106},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F name is not defined;\n",[17,109,110],{},"When you declare something inside a function, you can't reach it from outside.",[17,112,113],{},"Functions are affected by lexical scope too:",[41,115,117],{"className":43,"code":116,"language":45,"meta":46,"style":46},"function sayHi() {\n  function sayName() {\n    console.log('Ray');\n  }\n}\n\nsayName(); \u002F\u002F sayName is not defined;\n",[48,118,119,127,137,153,158,163,170],{"__ignoreMap":46},[51,120,121,123,125],{"class":53,"line":54},[51,122,58],{"class":57},[51,124,62],{"class":61},[51,126,66],{"class":65},[51,128,129,132,135],{"class":53,"line":69},[51,130,131],{"class":57},"  function",[51,133,134],{"class":61}," sayName",[51,136,66],{"class":65},[51,138,139,142,144,147,150],{"class":53,"line":88},[51,140,141],{"class":65},"    console.",[51,143,100],{"class":61},[51,145,146],{"class":65},"(",[51,148,149],{"class":81},"'Ray'",[51,151,152],{"class":65},");\n",[51,154,155],{"class":53,"line":94},[51,156,157],{"class":65},"  }\n",[51,159,161],{"class":53,"line":160},5,[51,162,91],{"class":65},[51,164,166],{"class":53,"line":165},6,[51,167,169],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":168},true,"\n",[51,171,173,176,179],{"class":53,"line":172},7,[51,174,175],{"class":61},"sayName",[51,177,178],{"class":65},"(); ",[51,180,181],{"class":106},"\u002F\u002F sayName is not defined;\n",[12,183,185],{"id":184},"static-scope-dynamic-scope","Static Scope & Dynamic Scope",[17,187,188],{},"Once you start talking about lexical scope, you end up talking about how JavaScript actually works under the hood. JavaScript belongs to the static scope camp. Static scope means the scope gets decided at the moment the code is parsed.",[17,190,191],{},[27,192],{"alt":193,"src":194},"Static scope","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-12%2015.53.54.png",[17,196,197],{},"Dynamic scope is the opposite. With dynamic scope, the scope only gets decided when the function is actually called.",[17,199,200],{},[27,201],{"alt":202,"src":203},"Recap","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-04-12%2015.55.14.png",[17,205,206],{},"Most programming languages use static scope — C, C++, C#, Python, Java, and so on all fall into the static-scope camp.",[17,208,209],{},"Since JavaScript uses static scope, the scope is already decided by the time the code runs. I've repeated this a few times already, so let me just show you with some code:",[41,211,213],{"className":43,"code":212,"language":45,"meta":46,"style":46},"var value = 1; \u002F\u002F global variable\nfunction fu1 {\n  console.log(value); \u002F\u002F 1\n}\nfunction fu2 {\n  var value = 2; \u002F\u002F local variable\n  fu1();\n}\nfu2();\n",[48,214,215,235,245,258,262,271,287,295,300],{"__ignoreMap":46},[51,216,217,220,223,225,229,232],{"class":53,"line":54},[51,218,219],{"class":57},"var",[51,221,222],{"class":65}," value ",[51,224,78],{"class":57},[51,226,228],{"class":227},"sCcAr"," 1",[51,230,231],{"class":65},"; ",[51,233,234],{"class":106},"\u002F\u002F global variable\n",[51,236,237,239,242],{"class":53,"line":69},[51,238,58],{"class":57},[51,240,241],{"class":61}," fu1",[51,243,244],{"class":65}," {\n",[51,246,247,250,252,255],{"class":53,"line":88},[51,248,249],{"class":65},"  console.",[51,251,100],{"class":61},[51,253,254],{"class":65},"(value); ",[51,256,257],{"class":106},"\u002F\u002F 1\n",[51,259,260],{"class":53,"line":94},[51,261,91],{"class":65},[51,263,264,266,269],{"class":53,"line":160},[51,265,58],{"class":57},[51,267,268],{"class":61}," fu2",[51,270,244],{"class":65},[51,272,273,275,277,279,282,284],{"class":53,"line":165},[51,274,72],{"class":57},[51,276,222],{"class":65},[51,278,78],{"class":57},[51,280,281],{"class":227}," 2",[51,283,231],{"class":65},[51,285,286],{"class":106},"\u002F\u002F local variable\n",[51,288,289,292],{"class":53,"line":172},[51,290,291],{"class":61},"  fu1",[51,293,294],{"class":65},"();\n",[51,296,298],{"class":53,"line":297},8,[51,299,91],{"class":65},[51,301,303,306],{"class":53,"line":302},9,[51,304,305],{"class":61},"fu2",[51,307,294],{"class":65},[17,309,310,311,314,315,317,318,320,321,324,325,328,329,332],{},"Like I said, the scope is decided when the code runs, so the ",[48,312,313],{},"var value = 2"," inside ",[48,316,305],{}," only lives inside ",[48,319,305],{},", while ",[48,322,323],{},"var value = 1;"," belongs to the global environment. That's why ",[48,326,327],{},"fu1"," outputs ",[48,330,331],{},"1",". There's an extra concept hiding in here too — the scope chain — but I'll save that for later. For now, just know one thing: when the current scope doesn't have the variable, JavaScript walks outward layer by layer looking for it.",[17,334,335],{},"So what about dynamic scope? With dynamic scope, you only know the scope when the code actually runs.",[41,337,339],{"className":43,"code":338,"language":45,"meta":46,"style":46},"var value = 1;\nfunction fu1 {\n  console.log(value); \u002F\u002F 2\n}\nfunction fu2 {\n  var value = 2;\n  fu1();\n}\nfu2();\n",[48,340,341,353,361,372,376,384,396,402,406],{"__ignoreMap":46},[51,342,343,345,347,349,351],{"class":53,"line":54},[51,344,219],{"class":57},[51,346,222],{"class":65},[51,348,78],{"class":57},[51,350,228],{"class":227},[51,352,85],{"class":65},[51,354,355,357,359],{"class":53,"line":69},[51,356,58],{"class":57},[51,358,241],{"class":61},[51,360,244],{"class":65},[51,362,363,365,367,369],{"class":53,"line":88},[51,364,249],{"class":65},[51,366,100],{"class":61},[51,368,254],{"class":65},[51,370,371],{"class":106},"\u002F\u002F 2\n",[51,373,374],{"class":53,"line":94},[51,375,91],{"class":65},[51,377,378,380,382],{"class":53,"line":160},[51,379,58],{"class":57},[51,381,268],{"class":61},[51,383,244],{"class":65},[51,385,386,388,390,392,394],{"class":53,"line":165},[51,387,72],{"class":57},[51,389,222],{"class":65},[51,391,78],{"class":57},[51,393,281],{"class":227},[51,395,85],{"class":65},[51,397,398,400],{"class":53,"line":172},[51,399,291],{"class":61},[51,401,294],{"class":65},[51,403,404],{"class":53,"line":297},[51,405,91],{"class":65},[51,407,408,410],{"class":53,"line":302},[51,409,305],{"class":61},[51,411,294],{"class":65},[17,413,414,415,417,418,421,422,425,426,428],{},"Here, because ",[48,416,305],{}," re-declares ",[48,419,420],{},"var value = 2;",", the ",[48,423,424],{},"value"," that ",[48,427,327],{}," actually grabs ends up being 2.",[12,430,432],{"id":431},"references","References",[434,435,436],"ul",{},[437,438,439],"li",{},[440,441,445],"a",{"href":442,"rel":443},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[444],"nofollow","Hexschool - JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[447,448,449],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .